01:04:39,600 --> 01:04:44,480
and a community member asked me this hilarious 
question that I think it's something a lot of  

733
01:04:44,480 --> 01:04:48,080
people are thinking about. So this is 
Patrick [inaudible 01:04:47]. I worked  

734
01:04:48,080 --> 01:04:53,040
with him at Airbnb. He says ask what he's 
encouraging his kids to learn to prepare  

735
01:04:53,040 --> 01:04:57,360
for the future. I'm worried my 6-year-old by 
the year 2036 will face a lot of competition  

736
01:04:57,360 --> 01:05:02,320
trying to get into the top roofing or 
plumbing programs and need a backup plan.

737
01:05:02,320 --> 01:05:07,920
That's funny. So our kids, we have a 
10 year old and eight year old twins,  

738
01:05:07,920 --> 01:05:17,440
so they're still pretty young. It's amazing how 
AI native they are. It's completely normal to  

739
01:05:17,440 --> 01:05:23,680
them that there are self-driving cars. That 
they can talk to AI all day long. They have  

740
01:05:23,680 --> 01:05:30,320
full conversations with Chat GPT and Alexa 
and everything else. I don't know, who knows  

741
01:05:30,320 --> 01:05:36,960
what the future holds? I think things like coding 
skills are going to be relevant for a long time,  

742
01:05:36,960 --> 01:05:44,160
who knows? But I think if you teach your 
kids to be curious, to be independent, to  

743
01:05:44,160 --> 01:05:50,400
be self-confident, you teach them how to think, I 
don't know what the future holds, but I think that  

744
01:05:50,400 --> 01:05:54,880
those are going to be skills that are going to 
be important in any configuration of the future.  

745
01:05:54,880 --> 01:06:02,320
And so it's not like we have all the answers, but 
that's how Elizabeth and I think about our kids.

746
01:06:02,320 --> 01:06:05,760
And do you find that AI... There's a 
lot of talk about AI tutoring. Is that  

747
01:06:05,760 --> 01:06:09,120
something you guys are doing? 
I know they're using Chat GPT,  

748
01:06:09,120 --> 01:06:12,640
I love all the photos you post where they're 
playing with prompts and stuff, but I guess  

749
01:06:12,640 --> 01:06:16,720
is there anything there you're experimenting with 
or you think is going to become really important?

750
01:06:16,720 --> 01:06:26,560
This is something that... It's maybe the most 
important thing that AI could do. Maybe that's  

751
01:06:26,560 --> 01:06:31,520
a grand statement. There are lots of important 
things that AI can do, including speeding up  

752
01:06:31,520 --> 01:06:35,760
the pace of fundamental science research and 
discovery, which maybe is actually the most  

753
01:06:35,760 --> 01:06:40,960
important thing AI can do. But one of the 
most important things would be personalized  

754
01:06:40,960 --> 01:06:46,720
tutoring. And it kind of blows my mind that 
there is still... I know there are a bunch of  

755
01:06:46,720 --> 01:06:53,520
good products out there. Khan Academy does great 
things. They're a wonderful partner of ours. Vinod  

756
01:06:53,520 --> 01:06:58,720
Khosla has a non-profit that's doing some really 
interesting stuff in this space and is making an  

757
01:06:58,720 --> 01:07:08,640
impact. But I'm kind of surprised that there 
isn't a 2 billion kid AI personalized tutoring  

758
01:07:08,640 --> 01:07:16,000
thing because the models are good enough to do it 
now, and every study out there that's ever been  

759
01:07:16,000 --> 01:07:23,840
done seems to show that when you have... Like, 
education is still important, but when you combine  

760
01:07:23,840 --> 01:07:31,360
that with personalized tutoring, you get multiple 
standard deviation improvements in learning speed. 

761
01:07:31,360 --> 01:07:38,960
And so it's uncontroversial, it's good for kids, 
it's free. Chat GPT is free, you don't need to  

762
01:07:38,960 --> 01:07:43,680
pay, and the models are good enough. It still just 
kind of blows my mind that there isn't something  

763
01:07:43,680 --> 01:07:51,760
amazing out there that our kids are using and your 
future kids are using, and people in all sorts of  

764
01:07:51,760 --> 01:07:57,040
places around the world that aren't as lucky as 
our kids to be able to have this sort of built-in,  

765
01:07:57,040 --> 01:08:04,240
solid education. Again, Chat GPT is free. People 
have Android devices everywhere. I really just  

766
01:08:04,240 --> 01:08:08,400
think this could change the world and I'm 
surprised it doesn't exist and I want it to exist.

767
01:08:08,400 --> 01:08:11,280
This kind of touches on something I want 
to spend a little time on, which is a lot  

768
01:08:11,280 --> 01:08:16,400
of people also worry a lot about AI, where it's 
going, they worry about jobs it's going to take,  

769
01:08:16,400 --> 01:08:22,800
they worry about the super intelligence squashing 
humanity in the future. What's your perspective  

770
01:08:23,360 --> 01:08:27,680
on that and just the optimistic case 
that I think people need to hear?

771
01:08:27,680 --> 01:08:32,320
I mean, I'm a big technology optimist. I 
think if you look over the last 200 years,  

772
01:08:33,520 --> 01:08:39,040
maybe more, technology has driven a lot 
of the advancements that have made us the  

773
01:08:39,040 --> 01:08:43,760
world and the society that we are today. 
It drives economic advancements, it drives  

774
01:08:45,200 --> 01:08:49,760
geopolitical advancements, quality of 
life, longevity advancement. I mean,  

775
01:08:49,760 --> 01:08:57,680
technology's at the root of just about everything, 
so I think there are very few examples where  

776
01:08:58,480 --> 01:09:00,076
this is anything but a great thing over the longer 
term. That doesn't mean that there aren't...

777
01:09:00,076 --> 01:09:05,200
... a great thing over the longer term. That 
doesn't mean that there aren't temporary  

778
01:09:05,200 --> 01:09:10,400
dislocations or where there aren't individuals 
that are impacted, and that matters too. So  

779
01:09:10,400 --> 01:09:13,840
it can't just be that the average is good. 
You've got to also think about how you take  

780
01:09:13,840 --> 01:09:21,440
care of each individual person as best you can.
It is something that we think a lot about and as  

781
01:09:21,440 --> 01:09:28,720
we work with the administration, as we work with 
policy, we try and help wherever we can. We do a  

782
01:09:28,720 --> 01:09:36,960
lot with education. One of the benefits here is 
that ChatGPT is also perhaps the best reskilling  

783
01:09:36,960 --> 01:09:40,720
app you could possibly want. It knows a lot 
of things. It can teach you a lot of things  

784
01:09:40,720 --> 01:09:48,240
if you're interested in learning new things.
These are very real issues. I'm super optimistic  

785
01:09:48,240 --> 01:09:52,560
about the long run, and we're going to 
need to do everything we can as a society  

786
01:09:52,560 --> 01:09:59,280
to ensure that we make this transition as 
graceful and as well-supported as we can.

787
01:09:59,280 --> 01:10:03,280
To give people a sense of where things might be 
going. That's a big question in a lot of people's  

788
01:10:03,280 --> 01:10:09,360
minds. So someone asked this question that I love, 
which is, "AI is already changing, creative work  

789
01:10:09,360 --> 01:10:13,920
in a lot of different ways, writing and design 
and coding, what do you think is the next big  

790
01:10:13,920 --> 01:10:19,120
leap? What should we be thinking is the next 
big leap in AI-assisted creativity specifically,  

791
01:10:19,120 --> 01:10:23,200
and then just broadly, where do you think things 
are going to be going in the next few years?"

792
01:10:23,200 --> 01:10:29,200
Yeah. This is also an area where I'm a big 
optimist. If you look at Sora, for example.  

793
01:10:29,200 --> 01:10:35,520
I mean we talked about ImageGen earlier and the 
absolute fount of creativity that people are  

794
01:10:35,520 --> 01:10:42,400
putting across Twitter and Instagram and other 
places. I am the world's worst artist like the  

795
01:10:42,400 --> 01:10:51,520
worst. Maybe the only thing I'm worse at than art 
is singing. Give me a pencil and a pad of paper  

796
01:10:51,520 --> 01:11:01,920
and I can't draw better than our eight-year-old. 
But give me ImageGen and I can think some creative  

797
01:11:01,920 --> 01:11:05,840
thoughts and put something into the model 
and suddenly have output that I couldn't  

798
01:11:05,840 --> 01:11:13,120
have possibly done myself. That's pretty cool.
Even you look at folks that are really talented.  

799
01:11:13,120 --> 01:11:18,480
I was talking to a director recently about 
Sora, someone who's directed films that we  

800
01:11:18,480 --> 01:11:27,520
would all know, and he was saying, for a film 
that he's doing, take the example of some sort  

801
01:11:27,520 --> 01:11:35,040
of sci-fi-ish, think of Star Wars, and you've got 
some scene where there's a plane zooming into some  

802
01:11:35,040 --> 01:11:40,000
Death Star-like thing. And so you've got the 
plane looking at the whole planet, and then you  

803
01:11:40,000 --> 01:11:45,040
want to cut to a scene where the plane's kind of 
at the ground level, and all of a sudden you see  

804
01:11:45,040 --> 01:11:51,520
the city and everything else. How are we going 
to manage that cut scene? And that transition? 

805
01:11:51,520 --> 01:12:02,880
And he was saying, "In the world of two years 
ago, I would have paid a 3D effects company  

806
01:12:02,880 --> 01:12:08,000
a hundred grand and they would've taken a 
month, and they would've produced two versions  

807
01:12:08,000 --> 01:12:12,960
of this cut scene for me. And I would've 
evaluated them. We would've chosen one,  

808
01:12:12,960 --> 01:12:18,080
because what are you going to do? Pay another 
50 grand and wait another month. And we would've  

809
01:12:18,080 --> 01:12:25,120
just gone with it. And it would be fine. Movies 
are great. I love them. And there've been..." 

810
01:12:25,120 --> 01:12:30,000
Obviously, we can do great things with the 
technology that we've had, but you now look  

811
01:12:30,000 --> 01:12:35,040
at what you can do with Sora. And his point 
was, "Now, I can use Sora, our video model,  

812
01:12:35,040 --> 01:12:41,600
and I can get 50 different variations of this cut 
scene just me brainstorming into a prompt and the  

813
01:12:41,600 --> 01:12:47,200
model brainstorming a little bit with me. I've 
got 50 different versions. And then of course, I  

814
01:12:47,200 --> 01:12:52,000
can iterate off of those and refine them and take 
different ideas. And now I'm still going to go to  

815
01:12:52,000 --> 01:12:59,280
that 3D effects studio to produce the final one, 
but I'm going to go having brainstormed and had a  

816
01:12:59,280 --> 01:13:06,960
much more creative approach with an outcome that's 
much better. And I did that assisted by AI." 

817
01:13:07,920 --> 01:13:13,600
My personal view on creativity in general is that 
it's no one's going to... You don't type into  

818
01:13:13,600 --> 01:13:19,120
Sora like, "Make me a great movie." It requires 
creativity and ingenuity, and all these things,  

819
01:13:19,120 --> 01:13:24,960
but it can help you explore more. It can help 
you get to a better final result. So, again,  

820
01:13:24,960 --> 01:13:31,040
I tend to be an optimist in most things, but 
actually, I think there's a very good story here.

821
01:13:31,040 --> 01:13:34,720
I know Sam Altman, I think it was him who tweeted 
recently, the creative writing piece that you  

822
01:13:34,720 --> 01:13:39,040
guys are working on where it's... He is very 
bad at writing creative stuff, and he shared  

823
01:13:39,040 --> 01:13:43,440
an example where it's actually really good. 
I imagine that's another area of investment.

824
01:13:43,440 --> 01:13:46,880
Yeah, there's some exciting 
stuff happening internally  

825
01:13:47,920 --> 01:13:52,800
with some new research techniques. We'll have 
more to say about that at some point. But yeah,  

826
01:13:52,800 --> 01:13:58,080
Sam sometimes likes to show off 
some of the stuff that's coming,  

827
01:13:58,640 --> 01:14:03,840
which is smart. By the way, it's very 
indicative of this iterative deployment  

828
01:14:03,840 --> 01:14:10,240
philosophy. We don't have some breakthrough and 
keep it to ourselves forever, and then bestow it  

829
01:14:10,240 --> 01:14:15,360
upon the world someday. We kind of just talk 
about the things we're working on and share  

830
01:14:15,360 --> 01:14:22,400
when we can and launch early and often, and then 
iterate in public. I really like that philosophy.

831
01:14:22,400 --> 01:14:25,440
I love all these hints that a few things 
coming. I know you can't say too much.  

832
01:14:25,440 --> 01:14:29,600
You talked about how there might be a coding 
leap coming in the near future maybe by the  

833
01:14:29,600 --> 01:14:32,960
time this comes out. Is there anything 
else people should be thinking about,  

834
01:14:32,960 --> 01:14:38,000
might be coming in the near future? Any things 
you can tease that are interesting? Exciting?

835
01:14:38,000 --> 01:14:41,120
Man, this hasn't been enough for you?

836
01:14:41,760 --> 01:14:43,840
Only everything is getting better every day.

837
01:14:43,840 --> 01:14:48,960
Yeah. I'm like, man, I hope we get some of 
this stuff out before the episode launches so-

838
01:14:48,960 --> 01:14:49,840
This is your new timebox.

839
01:14:49,840 --> 01:15:00,320
... I don't piss people off. The amazing thing 
to me is we were talking earlier about how far  

840
01:15:00,320 --> 01:15:05,440
models have come in just a couple of years. If 
you went back to GPT-3, you'd be disgusted by  

841
01:15:05,440 --> 01:15:14,880
how bad it was, even though Lenny of two years ago 
was mind-blown by how good these were. And for a  

842
01:15:14,880 --> 01:15:21,680
long time, we were iterating every six to nine 
months on a new GPT model. It was like GPT-3,  

843
01:15:21,680 --> 01:15:29,520
GPT-3.5, 4, and now with this o-series 
of reasoning models, we're moving even  

844
01:15:29,520 --> 01:15:37,280
faster. Every roughly three months, maybe 
four months, there's a new o-series model,  

845
01:15:37,280 --> 01:15:45,680
and each of them is a step up in capability.
And so the capabilities of these models are  

846
01:15:45,680 --> 01:15:52,160
increasing at a massive pace. They're also 
getting cheaper as they scale. You look  

847
01:15:52,960 --> 01:15:58,560
at where we were even a couple of years 
ago. I think the original, I don't know,  

848
01:15:58,560 --> 01:16:04,400
what was it, GPT-3.5 or something 
was like 100 x the cost of GPT-4o  

849
01:16:04,400 --> 01:16:10,160
mini today in the API. A couple of years, 
you've gone down two orders of magnitude in  

850
01:16:10,880 --> 01:16:17,120
cost for much more intelligence. And so I 
don't know where there's another series of  

851
01:16:17,120 --> 01:16:20,720
trends like that in the world. Models are 
getting smarter, they're getting faster,  

852
01:16:20,720 --> 01:16:27,040
they're getting cheaper, and they're getting 
safer too. They hallucinate less every iteration. 

853
01:16:27,040 --> 01:16:37,680
And so the Morse Law and transistors becoming 
ubiquitous. That was a law around doubling the  

854
01:16:37,680 --> 01:16:42,720
number of transistors on a chip every 18 months. 
If you're talking about something where you're  

855
01:16:42,720 --> 01:16:51,120
getting 10 x every year, that's a massively 
steeper exponential. And it tells us that  

856
01:16:51,120 --> 01:16:57,120
the future is going to be very different than 
today. The thing I try and remind myself is,  

857
01:16:57,120 --> 01:17:03,440
the AI models that you're using today is 
the worst AI model you will ever use for  

858
01:17:03,440 --> 01:17:08,240
the rest of your life. And when you actually 
get that in your head, it's kind of wild.

859
01:17:08,240 --> 01:17:10,480
I was going to actually say the 
same thing, and that's the thing  

860
01:17:10,480 --> 01:17:13,680
that always sticks with me when I watch 
this thing. You're talking about Sora,  

861
01:17:13,680 --> 01:17:18,000
and I imagine many people hearing that are 
like, "No, no. It's not actually ready. It's  

862
01:17:18,000 --> 01:17:21,600
not good enough. It's not going to be as good 
as a movie I see in the theater." But the point  

863
01:17:21,600 --> 01:17:25,440
is what you just made that this is the worst 
it's going to be. It will only get better.

864
01:17:25,440 --> 01:17:32,080
Yeah, model maximalism. Just keep building 
for the capabilities that are almost there,  

865
01:17:32,080 --> 01:17:34,880
and the model's going to catch up and be amazing.

866
01:17:34,880 --> 01:17:36,800
Escape to where the puck is going to be.

867
01:17:36,800 --> 01:17:37,040
Yeah.

868
01:17:38,160 --> 01:17:41,040
This reminds me, I was just using... 
I was duplifying everything the other  

869
01:17:41,040 --> 01:17:43,028
day and I was just like, "What is taking so long."

870
01:17:43,028 --> 01:17:43,040
As one does.

871
01:17:43,040 --> 01:17:45,040
Just like cut... What was that?

872
01:17:45,040 --> 01:17:46,480
I said, as one does.

873
01:17:46,480 --> 01:17:48,560
As one does these days. I was just like,  

874
01:17:48,560 --> 01:17:53,440
"It's taking a minute to generate this image 
of my family in this amazing way." Come on,  

875
01:17:53,440 --> 01:17:57,200
what's taking so long. You just get so 
used to magic happening in front of you.

876
01:17:57,200 --> 01:17:58,960
Yeah, totally.

877
01:17:58,960 --> 01:18:03,760
Okay, final question. This is going to go in a 
completely different direction. A lot of people  

878
01:18:03,760 --> 01:18:09,920
asked about this. So famously, you led this 
project at Facebook called Libra, which is now  

879
01:18:09,920 --> 01:18:14,400
called Novi. A lot of people always wondered, 
"What happened there? That was a really cool  

880
01:18:14,400 --> 01:18:19,040
idea." I know some people have a sense there's 
regulation challenges, things like that. I don't  

881
01:18:19,040 --> 01:18:22,800
know if you've talked about this much. So I guess, 
could you just give people a brief summary of just  

882
01:18:22,800 --> 01:18:26,720
what is Libra? This project you working on, and 
just what happened, and how you feel about it?

883
01:18:26,720 --> 01:18:32,240
Yeah. I mean, David Marcus led it, and 
I happily work for him and with him. I  

884
01:18:32,240 --> 01:18:39,680
think he's a visionary and also a mentor 
and a friend. Honestly, Libra is probably  

885
01:18:39,680 --> 01:18:45,120
the biggest disappointment of my career. When 
I think about the problems we were solving,  

886
01:18:45,120 --> 01:18:49,600
which are very real problems. If you look 
at, for example, the remittance space,  

887
01:18:49,600 --> 01:18:55,120
people sending money to family members in other 
countries, it is maybe... I mean it's incredibly  

888
01:18:55,120 --> 01:19:01,360
regressive, right? People that don't have the 
money to spend are having to pay 20% to send  

889
01:19:01,360 --> 01:19:07,360
money home to their family. So outrageous 
fees, it takes multiple days, you have to  

890
01:19:07,360 --> 01:19:15,760
go then pick up cash from... It's all bad.
And here we are with 3 billion people using  

891
01:19:15,760 --> 01:19:20,800
WhatsApp all over the world, talking to each 
other every day, especially friends and family,  

892
01:19:20,800 --> 01:19:27,280
and exactly the kind of people who'd send money 
to each other. Why can't you send money as  

893
01:19:27,280 --> 01:19:34,000
immediately, as cheaply, as simply as you send 
a text message? It is one of those things when  

894
01:19:34,000 --> 01:19:41,520
you sit back and think about it, that should just 
exist. And that was what we set out to try and do. 

895
01:19:41,520 --> 01:19:46,560
Now, I don't think we played all of our cards 
perfectly. If I could go back and do things, there  

896
01:19:46,560 --> 01:19:53,360
are a bunch of things I would do differently.
We tried to get it all at once. We tried to  

897
01:19:53,360 --> 01:19:58,480
launch a new blockchain. It was a basket of 
currencies originally. It was integration  

898
01:19:58,480 --> 01:20:01,360
into WhatsApp and Messenger, and I think the 
whole world kind of went like, "Oh my God,  

899
01:20:01,360 --> 01:20:06,960
that's a lot of change at once." And it happened 
also to be at the time that Facebook was at the  

900
01:20:06,960 --> 01:20:14,720
absolute nadir of its reputation. And so that 
didn't help. It was also not the Messenger that  

901
01:20:14,720 --> 01:20:20,880
people wanted for this kind of change. We 
knew all that going in, but we went for it. 

902
01:20:21,760 --> 01:20:25,600
I think there are a bunch of ways that we could 
do that that would've introduced the change a  

903
01:20:25,600 --> 01:20:32,640
little bit more gently, maybe still gotten 
to that same outcome, but fewer new things  

904
01:20:32,640 --> 01:20:38,320
at once and introduced the new things one at a 
time. Who knows? Those were decisions we made  

905
01:20:38,320 --> 01:20:44,480
together. So we all own them. Certainly, I 
own them. But it fundamentally disappoints  

906
01:20:44,480 --> 01:20:48,640
me that this doesn't exist in the world today 
because the world would be a better place if  

907
01:20:48,640 --> 01:20:54,400
we'd been able to ship that product. I would 
be able to send you 50 cents in WhatsApp for  

908
01:20:54,400 --> 01:20:58,880
free. It would settle instantly. Everybody would 
have a balance in their WhatsApp account. We'd  

909
01:20:58,880 --> 01:21:05,120
be transact... I mean, it should exist.
I don't know. To be honest, the current  

910
01:21:05,120 --> 01:21:08,560
administration is super friendly 
to crypto. Facebook's reputation,  

911
01:21:08,560 --> 01:21:13,760
Meta's reputation is in a very different 
place. Maybe they should go build it now.

912
01:21:13,760 --> 01:21:16,000
I was looking at the history 
of it, and apparently,  

913
01:21:16,000 --> 01:21:19,760
they sold the tech to some private 
equity company for 200 million bucks.

914
01:21:19,760 --> 01:21:22,000
